# Airbnb Analytics - Bus Matrix

## Purpose

The bus matrix maps business processes (facts) against dimensions.

---

## Bus Matrix

| Business Process | Fact Table | dim_date ⚪ | dim_listing 🟡 | dim_host 🔵 | dim_neighbourhood ⚪ | dim_reviewer 🟡 | dim_amenity ⚪ |
|------------------|------------|:----------:|:--------------:|:-----------:|:-------------------:|:---------------:|:--------------:|
| Listing Performance Snapshot | `fct_listing_snapshot` | ✓ | ✓ | ○ | ○ | — | ○ |
| Guest Reviews | `fct_reviews` | ✓ | ✓ | ○ | ○ | ✓ | ○ |

---

## Legend

### Relationship Symbols

| Symbol | Meaning |
|:------:|---------|
| ✓ | Direct relationship |
| ○ | Indirect relationship (available through another dimension) |
| — | Not applicable |

### Dimension Types

| Symbol | Type | Description |
|:------:|------|-------------|
| ⚪ | Type 0 | Static dimension (no history maintained) |
| 🟡 | Type 1 | Changes overwrite existing values (history is not preserved) |
| 🔵 | Type 2 | Changes create new dimension versions to preserve history |

---

## Supporting Structure

### `bridge_listing_amenity`

Resolves the many-to-many relationship between `dim_listing` and `dim_amenity`, enabling analysis of listings by their available amenities.

---

## Design Notes

- `dim_host` is implemented as an **SCD Type 2** using a dbt snapshot because host attributes (such as Superhost status and response rates) may change over time and historical tracking is valuable.
- `dim_listing` is implemented as an **SCD Type 1**. Changes to descriptive listing attributes overwrite existing values, while historical listing metrics are captured separately in `fct_listing_snapshot`.
- `dim_reviewer` is implemented as an **SCD Type 1** because preserving historical reviewer information is not required for this project.
- `dim_date`, `dim_neighbourhood`, and `dim_amenity` are implemented as **Type 0** dimensions because they are treated as static reference data.
- `fct_listing_snapshot` stores historical listing measures such as price, availability, review counts, and review scores, enabling trend and point-in-time analysis.